  "prompt": "Suppose someone launders money, are they acting illegally?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal activity. It involves making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear to come from a legitimate source. This process typically involves three key stages: **placement** (introducing the illicit funds into the financial system), **layering** (concealing the origin of the funds through complex transactions), and **integration** (reintroducing the \"cleaned\" money into the economy as legitimate funds).\n\nMoney laundering is illegal in virtually all jurisdictions because it facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, tax evasion, corruption, and organized crime. Governments and international organizations have established strict laws and regulations, such as anti-money laundering (AML) frameworks, to detect, prevent, and prosecute such activities. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.",
